</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong rejected U.N. criticism that it has mistreated some of the 50,000 
Vietnamese "boat people" who have flocked to the British colony. A team from 
the Geneva headquarters of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees had warned 
that serious overcrowding would lead to fresh outbreaks of violence among 
frustrated inmates of refugee camps. "The space is less than the space given to 
people in prison here. It is even less than what is supposed to be given here 
for a dog," Omar Bakhet, head of the agency's technical support unit, said on 
local radio. However, Hong Kong's refugee coordinator, Mike Hanson, called the 
criticism "entirely unreasonable" and noted that "we can't build new 
accommodations overnight." 
