<P>
BUSINESS INVENTORIES UP, SALES DIP IN JUNE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Business inventories rose 0.4% in June as business sales fell 0.3%, the 
government said Monday. Analysts said the report was in line with the economic 
"soft landing" sought by the Federal Reserve Board -- slow but continued growth 
with low inflation. 
</P>
<P>
Inventories often rise during slow economic growth as production exceeds 
demand, a process that sometimes leads to a loss of jobs as businesses cut 
their output. 
</P>
