<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An experimental program to bring arts to troubled teen-agers in San Francisco 
has been praised as a success, but there is a problem: money. The California 
Arts Council renewed a $11,000 grant for the project, in which three artists 
work part-time with youths in the city's juvenile jail and with the privately 
run Charila Home for abused girls. However, there is no city money to help 
finance the program. Sponsors are now looking for private funds to match the 
state grant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
