<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOCAL; 
</P>
<P>
COUNCIL OKS GRAFFITI ORDINANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Los Angeles City Council approved an ordinance today that would allow city 
workers to remove graffiti from private property with the owner's consent at 
city expense -- or else. 
</P>
<P>
The council's 14-0 vote sent the ordinance to the mayor, who has 10 days to 
sign the measure into law. 
</P>
<P>
If a property owner should refuse permission and fail to remove the graffiti on 
his own, the city could do the job and charge the owner for the work. 
</P>
<P>
The ordinance is a revision of a measure considered last week that would have 
cited owners with a misdemeanor for not complying. 
</P>
<P>
The new ordinance means that if someone complains about graffiti on a privately 
owned building, the city will contact the owner and ask permission to remove it 
at city expense. If the owner refuses, the city will give him 15 days to remove 
the graffiti on his own. If it remains after 15 days, the city will remove it 
without consent and place a lien on the property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
